A massive fire broke out at Gul Plaza, a multi-storey shopping mall on M.A. Jinnah Road, Karachi, late Saturday night, rapidly spreading due to highly flammable goods and poor ventilation. A massive fire broke out at Gul Plaza, a multi-storey shopping mall on M.A. Jinnah Road, Karachi, late Saturday night, rapidly spreading due to highly flammable goods and poor ventilation. The blaze caused severe structural damage, with parts of the building collapsing, and adjacent structures showing cracks. Rescue operations have been challenging, with dense smoke, extreme heat, and weakened pillars hampering access. At least six people, including a firefighter, have died, while more than 20 others were injured, and dozens remain trapped inside. Sindh Rangers, Pakistan Navy, and over 20 fire tenders are involved in the ongoing rescue effort. Authorities have raised serious concerns about fire safety compliance in the plaza, which houses over 1,200 shops. The Sindh Chief Minister has ordered a detailed inquiry, and the Prime Minister has expressed condolences, ensuring medical care and support for the affected families. 

Iran Protests & Crackdown Updates (Jan 2026)
Nationwide protests erupted on 28 Dec 2025 due to economic hardship, inflation, job losses, and rising living costs. What began as economic demonstrations quickly turned into widespread anti-government protests across major cities, including Tehran, Karaj, Mashhad, and Kurdish regions.

Authorities responded with a violent crackdown using the IRGC and Basij militias, live ammunition, and heavy weapons. Streets are under heavy patrols, and while public protests have subsided, tensions remain high. A near-total internet blackout since 8 Jan 2026 limited reporting, though some connectivity is returning.

Casualty estimates vary widely: official reports confirm ~5,000 killed, while activists and Iranian doctors report up to 16,500 deaths and 330,000 injuries. Tens of thousands have been arrested, with some facing fast-track trials and death sentences.

Supreme Leader Khamenei blamed foreign powers for the unrest, while the US and international bodies condemned the crackdown and threatened sanctions. On the ground, cities show heavy security, closed businesses, and sporadic underground resistance. Diaspora protests continue in cities like Los Angeles and London.
